<subSubSection id="C372657C5759FFE8DFFAFE537A95FD79" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BD736F75759FFE8DFFAFE537A95FD79" blockId="11.[151,1437,254,1649]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFFAFE537875FDC9" bold="true" box="[199,314,506,533]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Size small, length 
<quantity id="4C909B125759FFE8DD25FE527BEDFDC9" box="[536,674,507,533]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.7" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.7 mm</quantity>
; dorsal ground color light to medium reddish brown, immaculate or nearly so (
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DE33FDB67817FDE5" box="[270,344,542,569]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1792,1817]" captionTargetBox="[354,1209,529,1746]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[346,1242,548,1765]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Xanthonia species, dorsal habitus. 1) X. angulata (Bastrop Co., Texas); 2) X. dentata (Jeff Davis Co., Texas); 3) X. furcata (Wood Co., Texas); 4) X. nitida (Pecos Co., Texas); 5) X. parva (Kerr Co., Texas); 6) X. picturata (Robertson Co., Texas); 7) X. querci (Val Verde Co., Texas); 8) X. texana (Bandera Co., Texas); 9) X. villosula (Bossier Parish, Louisiana). Images to scale, scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414688" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414688/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DE58FDB778CBFDE5" box="[357,388,542,569]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–60" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1565,1590]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,174,1521]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[227,1361,166,1545]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 55–60. Xanthonia species, types and type labels. 55) X. dentata; 56) X. parva; 57) X. hirsuta; 58) X. angulata; 59) X. striata, 60) X. nitida." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414698" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414698/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">56</figureCitation>
), venter of body light to medium brown; hairs on intervals reclined and in single rows, hairs arising from punctures appressed nearly as long as those on intervals; ventral tooth of profemur obsolete to absent; margins of ventrites III-V serrate (
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DD21FDCE7B25FD5D" box="[540,618,615,641]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1053,1078]" captionTargetBox="[266,1322,166,1031]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[266,1322,166,1034]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17–26. Xanthonia species, margins of ventrites III–V. 17) X. dentata; 18) X. parva; 19) X. villosula; 20) X. angulata. Figs. 21–22. Xanthonia species, profemora. 21) X. vagans; 22) X. marquai; 23) X. picturata; 24) X. hirsuta; 25) X. texana; 26) X. parva." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414694" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414694/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig 18</figureCitation>
); median lobe of male genitalia gradually tapered distally, apex rounded with shallow v-shaped incision and short broad lobe on each side (
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DC42FD227A82FD79" box="[895,973,651,677]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–54" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1724,1749]" captionTargetBox="[254,1348,323,1680]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[227,1361,330,1705]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 27–54. Xanthonia species, en-face and lateral view of median lobe. 27) X. vagans (Palmerlee, Arizona); 28–29) X. vagans (Chisos Mts., Texas); 30–31) X. marquai (Jeff Davis Co., Texas); 32–33) X. picturata (Gonzales, Texas); 34–35) X. parva (Kerr Co., Texas); 36) X. villosula (Miller, Indiana); 37) X. villosula (Dallas, Texas); 38–39) X. villosula (Natchez, Mississippi); 40) X. dentata (Socorro Co., New Mexico); 41) X. dentata (Sapello, New Mexico); 42) X. dentata (Chisos Mts., Texas); 43–44) X. dentata (Cloudcroft, New Mexico); 45–46) X. hirsuta (Dallas, Texas); 47–49) X. texana (Victoria, Texas); 50) X. nitida (San Antonio, Texas); 51–52) X. nitida (Dallas, Texas); 53–54) X. querci (Dallas, Texas). All figures from Weisman (1960), except 30–31 and 32–33." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414696" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414696/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig 34</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C372657C5759FFE8DFFAFD077A59FAA9" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD736F75759FFE8DFFAFD07782CFB39" blockId="11.[151,1437,254,1649]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFFAFD07781EFD15" bold="true" box="[199,337,686,713]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Description</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DE5CFD0778EAFD15" bold="true" box="[353,421,686,713]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Color</emphasis>
: Head light reddish brown, labrum and antennae slightly lighter shade of reddish brown. Pronotum and elytra light to medium reddish brown, elytra without dark pattern or at most with vague traces of a pattern (
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DFC8FD5E787BFCCD" box="[245,308,758,785]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1792,1817]" captionTargetBox="[354,1209,529,1746]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[346,1242,548,1765]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Xanthonia species, dorsal habitus. 1) X. angulata (Bastrop Co., Texas); 2) X. dentata (Jeff Davis Co., Texas); 3) X. furcata (Wood Co., Texas); 4) X. nitida (Pecos Co., Texas); 5) X. parva (Kerr Co., Texas); 6) X. picturata (Robertson Co., Texas); 7) X. querci (Val Verde Co., Texas); 8) X. texana (Bandera Co., Texas); 9) X. villosula (Bossier Parish, Louisiana). Images to scale, scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414688" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414688/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DE7CFD5F782EFCCD" box="[321,353,758,785]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–60" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1565,1590]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,174,1521]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[227,1361,166,1545]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 55–60. Xanthonia species, types and type labels. 55) X. dentata; 56) X. parva; 57) X. hirsuta; 58) X. angulata; 59) X. striata, 60) X. nitida." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414698" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414698/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">56</figureCitation>
). Venter light to medium brownish. Legs light reddish brown. 
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DB1AFD5E7D25FCCD" bold="true" box="[1063,1130,759,785]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Form</emphasis>
: Length 
<quantity id="4C909B125759FFE8DBECFD5E7C16FCCD" box="[1233,1369,759,785]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.7" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.7 mm</quantity>
Head densely and coarsely punctate throughout and with short golden closely-appressed pubescence, face with median line faintly impressed on vertex, inter-antennal area nearly flat. Pronotum densely and coarsely punctate with short fine golden recumbent pubescence, width averaging 1.27 times length, widest at middle; lateral margins evenly broadly rounded in dorsal view; anterior transverse depression and lateral impressions obscure. Elytra length averaging 1.38 times their combined width, 2.35 times length of pronotum; basal callosity poorly developed; punctures confused over most of disc and base, tending to form rows at suture and along lateral margins and apex; punctures as large or slightly larger than spaces between punctures; intervals at lateral margins and apex slightly elevated; pubescence composed of reclining hair arranged in single lines on intervals and recurved appressed hairs arising from punctures nearly as long as erect hairs. Metasternum smooth medially, finely densely punctate laterally. Abdomen with ridge of lateral margins of ventrites III–V serrate, often irregularly serrate (
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DB6AFBF67DEAFBA5" box="[1111,1189,1119,1145]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1053,1078]" captionTargetBox="[266,1322,166,1031]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[266,1322,166,1034]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17–26. Xanthonia species, margins of ventrites III–V. 17) X. dentata; 18) X. parva; 19) X. villosula; 20) X. angulata. Figs. 21–22. Xanthonia species, profemora. 21) X. vagans; 22) X. marquai; 23) X. picturata; 24) X. hirsuta; 25) X. texana; 26) X. parva." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414694" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414694/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig 18</figureCitation>
); last ventrite of male flat without tubercles. Ventral tooth obsolete to absent on all femora. Median lobe of male genitalia in en-face view slightly tapered distally, apex broad, with shallow broad v-shaped incision that defines short round lobe on each side (
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DFEEFB627818FB39" box="[211,343,1226,1253]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–54" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1724,1749]" captionTargetBox="[254,1348,323,1680]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[227,1361,330,1705]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 27–54. Xanthonia species, en-face and lateral view of median lobe. 27) X. vagans (Palmerlee, Arizona); 28–29) X. vagans (Chisos Mts., Texas); 30–31) X. marquai (Jeff Davis Co., Texas); 32–33) X. picturata (Gonzales, Texas); 34–35) X. parva (Kerr Co., Texas); 36) X. villosula (Miller, Indiana); 37) X. villosula (Dallas, Texas); 38–39) X. villosula (Natchez, Mississippi); 40) X. dentata (Socorro Co., New Mexico); 41) X. dentata (Sapello, New Mexico); 42) X. dentata (Chisos Mts., Texas); 43–44) X. dentata (Cloudcroft, New Mexico); 45–46) X. hirsuta (Dallas, Texas); 47–49) X. texana (Victoria, Texas); 50) X. nitida (San Antonio, Texas); 51–52) X. nitida (Dallas, Texas); 53–54) X. querci (Dallas, Texas). All figures from Weisman (1960), except 30–31 and 32–33." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3414696" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3414696/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs 34–35</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD736F75759FFE8DFFAFB467D6DFAD6" blockId="11.[151,1437,254,1649]" box="[199,1058,1263,1290]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFFAFB46785CFAD5" bold="true" box="[199,275,1263,1289]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Range</emphasis>
. Thus far known from a limited area of the Edwards Plateau (
<figureCitation id="13532A725759FFE8DCF5FB467D5BFAD6" box="[968,1044,1263,1290]" captionStart="MAPS 1–6" captionStartId="18.[151,223,1804,1829]" captionTargetBox="[276,1314,323,1756]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[264,1323,330,1762]" captionText="MAPS 1–6. Distribution of Xanthonia species. 1) X. vagans; 2) X. furcata (■), X. marquai (♦), X. nitida (●); 3) X. hirsuta; 4) X. picturata; 5) X. angulata (♦), X. dentata (●), X. querci (■); 6) X. parva (■), X. villosula (●)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3448931" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3448931/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Map 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD736F75759FFE8DFFAFABA7BCBFA8E" blockId="11.[151,1437,254,1649]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFFAFABA78D0FAF1" bold="true" box="[199,415,1298,1325]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Plant associations</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus id="54D388555759FFE8DED8FABA7B08FAF1" box="[485,583,1299,1325]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">holotype</typeStatus>
series was beaten from Lacey oak, 
<taxonomicName id="4C684D745759FFE8DCD1FABA7DAEFAF1" authority="Small" authorityName="Small" authorityYear="1901" box="[1004,1249,1299,1325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laceyi">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DCD1FABA7DD9FAF1" box="[1004,1174,1299,1325]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Quercus laceyi</emphasis>
Small
</taxonomicName>
(long-known in 
<collectingRegion id="49ACF8155759FFE8DFAAFA9E7997FA8D" box="[151,216,1335,1361]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Texas</collectingRegion>
as 
<taxonomicName id="4C684D745759FFE8DFC0FA9E7B38FA8E" authority="Mart. &amp; Gal." authorityName="Mart. &amp; Gal." box="[253,631,1335,1362]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glaucoides">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFC0FA9E7894FA8D" box="[253,475,1335,1361]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Quercus glaucoides</emphasis>
Mart. &amp; Gal.
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD736F75759FFE8DFFAFAF37A59FAA9" blockId="11.[151,1437,254,1649]" box="[199,790,1370,1397]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFFAFAF3788BFAA9" bold="true" box="[199,452,1370,1397]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Seasonal distribution</emphasis>
. Taken during April and May.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C372657C5759FFE8DFFAFAD679BEF9AD" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD736F75759FFE8DFFAFAD67812F9F5" blockId="11.[151,1437,254,1649]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFFAFAD6787BFA45" bold="true" box="[199,308,1407,1433]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Remarks</emphasis>
. This is the smallest member of the genus occurring in 
<collectingRegion id="49ACF8155759FFE8DCA6FAD67A93FA45" box="[923,988,1407,1433]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Texas</collectingRegion>
and not likely to be confused with other species with denticulate ventrite margins. It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C684D745759FFE8DC70FA0D7DECFA61" authority="Staines &amp; Weisman" authorityName="Staines &amp; Weisman" box="[845,1187,1443,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xanthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serrata">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DC70FA0D7AF2FA61" box="[845,957,1444,1469]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">X. serrata</emphasis>
Staines &amp; Weisman
</taxonomicName>
, another small species found in the eastern states but that species has a slightly differently shaped median lobe and distinct elytral pattern. Our Kerr County specimens are immaculate, but one specimen from Burnet County has a very faint indication of an elytral pattern.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD736F75759FFE8DFFAF99B79BEF9AD" blockId="11.[151,1437,254,1649]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B91CEAE55759FFE8DFFAF99B788FF991" bold="true" box="[199,448,1586,1613]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Specimens examined</emphasis>
. See 
<typeStatus id="54D388555759FFE8DD3DF99A7B74F991" box="[512,571,1587,1613]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">types</typeStatus>
cited above. The male genitalia of seven males from two localities were examined.
</paragraph>
